Apr 20 2009 	Beautiful Timeshare Resort	I just returned from Tahiti Village this week. I did a timeshare exchange through Interval International. This is a very nice timeshare resort. Beautiful rooms, great pool and lazy river, well landscaped, etc. There are 2 on site restaurants Tahiti Joe's and Denny's. Tahiti Joe's had good food and good service. Denny's was what you would expect from a Denny's. Poor service and mediocore food. They have free shuttle service to the Las Vegas strip which is about 2 miles down Las Vegas Blvd.Keep in mind that this is a timeshare resort, and they will want you to &quot;preview&quot; the resort. Go ahead, spend 2 hours and take the tour. Get some free dinner and show tickets. Just remember, do not purchase a timeshare from them. They will want to sell you a 2 bedroom unit for only $47,000. Ouch!!! If you like the resort and want to purchase a unit just google &quot;Tahiti Village Timeshare Resales&quot;. You will get a gazillion hits and can buy a unit for a fraction of what the developer wants. Also, look on Ebay.If you have a rental car make sure you visit Red Rock Canyon which is about 15 miles from Las Vegas. It will be the best $5.00 you spend while in Vegas.  If you want a real adventure, get up early and drive 160 miles to Zion National Park in Utah. It takes about 2 1/2 hours to get there. Once you get out of Vegas the speed limit is 75 mph. It costs $25.00 per car to get in the park. The place is absolutley beautiful. Great scenery and hiking. Bring a backpack to carry water and snacks. You won't be disappointed. Stay away from Grand Canyon West and the Grand Canyon Skywalk. It's a private enterprise on an Indian reservation, and it's a money hungry, cash grabbing, tourist trap. Visit the State and National Parks in the area and save your cash.If you decide to stay at Tahiti Village, you won't be disappointed in the accomodations. The place is beautiful. Just remember, it is a timeshare resort. Take the tour, but just say NO!!!	
