Jan 12 2009 	New Years Stay	Spent three nights over New Years in a Royal Tahitian suite in the big tower (Bld 6 I think). Wife’s parents are owners. After reading all the negative reviews we were very tentative about our trip and checked in expecting the worst. I am pleased to say our stay was pleasant in most aspects and we look forward to future visits. Service staff were polite and helpful.Rooms were clean, spacious, and well maintained. Large flat screen TV’s in each room and the master bath had a great spa bathtub and steam shower.House keeping does not come in every day, but this amenity was not necessary as we have no problem making our own beds, and besides, they promptly attended to any need we had – new towels, kitchen supplies, coffee, etc… they even came immediately to the room when we called about a spill. Our room was on the 8th floor and faced west. It was a busy weekend for airline traffic yet we could not hear any plane noise at all despite being able to see them come in on approach.We were not bothered by any harassing sales calls or sales people. Although I admit they hung around in packs and their were constant tours going on. But again, we hardly noticed, and experienced none of the hassles others have complained about.Now some downers:Although Tahiti Joes is a decent enough restaurant, don’t order any of the “spicy” foods unless you really like HOT. A wired idiosyncrasy is that you have to order cocktails from a separate server and pay a separate bar bill – that seems strange to us.We brought along the Wii for the kids, but the flat screens are mounted so flush to the walls you can’t slip a hand in to access input terminals. In the end I went to Radio Shack and bought RCA adaptors and then used the jacks from the DVD player on the main TV. The real downer of the place was that the big tower has ZERO internet service. I talked to someone about it and they say their tech company had a problem during construction and they were not expecting Wi-Fi for a while. Denny’s is the only free internet access available.If anyone in your party has trouble walking make sure you get a room close to the elevators, the big tower hallways are football fields long.Being a holiday weekend not much work was happening, but major construction is and will continue to be going on for some time. If you look at the resort map, phase III has only just broken ground on the entire eastern side of the resort. I can certainly see how this will be irritating especially with an east facing room.	
Jan 7 2009	Great Resort Rooms Very Large and Comfortable	My wife and I just returned from a 4 night stay at Tahiti Village. We had the 2 bedroom, 2 bath unit and shared it with another couple (my best friend and his wife). We stayed on the third floor of Building 5. The rooms were very large, it had a full well stocked kitchen in the living area and another well stocked kitchenette in the attached lock-off. The unit was approx. 1550 square feet. It was absolutely spotless and clean when we arrived. The unit looked brand new and like we were the first people to stay in it. The rooms were very well insulated so you didn't hear noise from any adjacent rooms. I read most of the other reviews and don't understand why they were so negative. Yes, the resort is not in the middle of the strip. It is located on the south end of the Las Vegas strip about 1 1/2 miles south of the Mandalay Bay resort. Yes, it is more convenient if you have a car. However, the shuttle service provided by Tahiti Village was more than adequate. It leaves every 1/2 hour and runs to around midnight. We took the shuttle to the Tropicana which was opposite the MGM, New York, New York and the Excaliber. Yes, the breakfast buffet wasn't that great. But overall I would say that this resort, though not perfect, is a good place to stay. I will definitely come back.	
