Sep 8 2008 	Mixed Experience	We saw the ad of this time share on TV with Alan Thicke. We made the initial reservations and after several phone calls and reviews of the internet we decided to upgrade to the 4 day/3 night stay at the actual resort. We already own a time share but we were open to new, REASONABLE opportunities.The first impression was pretty poor. The room we checked into initially had not been cleaned and prepared for new clients. As I had lugged our two heavily bags to this room, my wife and I were not happy. After a few choice words, we were moved to another room. The accomodations were comparable to the time share we own in Arkansas. It was very nice even though we were in the smaller side of the room. The bedroom and living room/kitchen had flat screen monitors mounted on the wall. The bathroom on this side had a a decent shower. However we when we upgraded, they forgot to include the renewal of the vows and the show tickets. We were told we had to do the tour before this could get resolved. Our tour was the next morning so we decided to do some sight seeing. Our first night in Las Vegas was great and we enjoyed our first time together alone since our daughter was conceived and born about a year and a half ago.The next morning we got up and went to the tour. This is where the mixed feelings began. The first part of the tour was not bad. Everyone was very polite. Our agent informed us that she wanted to show us their property and it would be up to us to determine if it fit with our life style and budget. There would be no pressure. The review of the full room was great and it was just beautiful. I could see my wife and I returning some time in the near future to use this property.However when we were informed of the price, $47k I was shocked. As soon as she thought we were beginning to decline, the pressure increased. When we fully and forcefully declined, they stated they wanted us to talk to someone to make sure we were treated fairly. However they brought over a &quot;sales manager&quot; to try to get us to make a more &quot;reasonable&quot; deal. After several declines, we were taken to the check out desk to get our money and coupons. Our sales agent said goodbye and explained how to get back to our room.It is a good property and should be a good investment if you can get them to negotiate the price down to $26k or less which is about $450 a month note. If their claim holds up about them being one of the few time share sellers who offer part of the property for all eternity, it is definitely a better deal with more negotiation power when you want to go to other places like Hawaii or Miami. It is definitely for families who have this type of disposable income.	
Sep 7 2008 	I was a little worried...	Just returned from a stay here 8/31-9/6. First off I was a bit worried after reading all of the reviews here. So to say the least I was a little skeptical that things would be ok.We arrived about 7pm on a Saturday evening which turned out to be an excellent time to arrive. The front desk had no line and we had our room keys within 3 minutes. We were put on the second floor of building 5 which has just opened. The room was as advertised and very nice. There was almost no evidence of anyone staying in the room previously. I think we were only the second occupants. One pan had a couple of scratches in it and everything else looked brand new.We had been through the murderous presentation about 3 years ago and knew it was not going to happen again so we were constantly on guard for the lead-ins to it. Every time we talked to a concierge we were asked if we wanted to do it to get free show tickets or a Grand Canyon tour but we were not pestered after saying no. In the casinos I found it effective to show the room key to the people trying to hook victims for the presentation and say &quot;Already staying there.&quot; They quickly moved to the next potential victim.The good...The staff was friendly, helpful and available when needed and unobtrusive when not.The room was clean and comfortable.The location is convenient but away from the strip.The steam shower was awesome.Housekeeping picked up towels and garbage left in the hall very quickly.The bad...Coffee. The weak stuff they pass off as coffee in the room is not fit to drink so plan on bringing your own or grabbing some locally before morning. The coffee maker used #2 Melitta type filters which we had to buy at the grocery store.The Pool. The pool is shallow and not shaded at all making it very warm. Too warm to be refreshing. The lazy river is still under construction and should be shaded from the afternoon sun by building 5. They also do not appear to be enforcing the rules of no glass in the pool area. We saw many people with beer bottles in and around the pool. Parking. As mentioned in other reviews the parking at this place sucks. Fortunately we were close to the south end of building 5 which is only a few steps from the new parking garage. If we were in any of the other buildings this would have really been an issue.Stairways. Being on the second floor and fairly fit we tend to use stairs instead of elevators. Unfortunately there is no access to the stairways from the first floor of the building. This forced us to walk almost 300 feet to the elevators and then back almost the entire length of the hall to our room. Not a huge deal but packing a weeks worth of groceries that far was no fun.Wi-Fi. Specifically the lack of it. Wi-Fi Internet service is not available in building 5. For a &quot;Nominal Fee&quot; of $11 a day you can get it on your TV in the room but I don't think I am alone in thinking $11 is not nominal. There were two workstations with excessive fees available in the &quot;business center&quot; (I would call it a closet) in the main lobby. There is no excuse for not having wi-fi in a brand new building. Free Wi-Fi is available in the Denny's restaurant next door to Tahiti Joe's. Fire Alarm. There is still construction going on in building 5 and Thursday morning about 8 am the fire alarm was set off forcing us to evacuate the building. We had to stand outside for about 10 minutes while they sorted it out. When we could get back in we had to wait around in the building lobby for a few minutes while they figured out how to unlock the elevators which were secured by the alarm. See the note about no first floor stairway access above.Housekeeping. Our room was toweled mid week and they did a fine job except they forgot to empty the garbage. This was not a big deal for us and I only mention it as some people would be put off by it. If you want housekeeping service more than just the one time during the week there is a $35 charge.Transportation. If you are going to stay here you really need a car if you want any flexibility. We had one so we did not use the shuttle but we saw people waiting for it almost all of the time. It appeared they only had 2 or 3 shuttles running. But they had about 20 shuttles available to ferry the presentation victims back and forth from their hotels on the strip. The Deuce strip bus can be caught across the street (Warm Springs) at the outlet mall. There was often a taxi waiting for a fare near the front entrance but I never saw more than one sitting there. There was a taxi queue across the street in front of the outlet mall.General stuff...For groceries there is a Food 4 Less store about 2 miles south on Las Vegas Blvd. Excellent prices and a good selection. We were pleased with our deli purchases there as well. There is also an Albertson's store about 3 miles east on Warm Springs at Eastern if you want a regular full service super market. For liquor Lee's Discount Liquor has about the best prices and selection I have seen around Vegas. They are located about 3 miles south on Las Vegas Blvd.For gas the Rebel station on the corner of Las Vegas and Warm Springs has about the best gas prices around and they also have E85 available.Parking on the strip is free in most of the casino parking garages. Just look for the self park signs. We used New York's garage for the south strip and Paris for the central strip. Downtown on Fremont use the Golden Nugget garage or the city garage just east of Fitzgeralds. Just make sure you get the ticket validated. Validation is only good for 3 hours so you need to go move the car if you are staying longer and don't want to pay. Do not use the Necropolis garage north of Fremont as Fitzgeralds will not validate it.In summary...I would never buy into this place nor would I subject myself to one of their sales presentations again. They will tell you it is only 2 hours but you will be lucky to get out of there with your wallet intact in less than 4 hours. The secondary market for Tahiti Village is alive and well. They will be happy to sell you a unit for 40-50k and make you think you got a good deal but you can find them in several places online for 10-25k. Three years ago in our presentation they started us at $37500 and as we were walking out the door they were trying for $7500 for the same deal. It is obvious they only have one objective in mind that being to get you to a presentation. They don't care if you already own since they want to &quot;upgrade&quot; you. I would definitely stay at Tahiti Village again. The rental rate is a bit excessive in my opinion at $200 plus a night but fortunately there are secondary rental opportunities available as well if you take a little time to look for them.	
Sep 6 2008 	Tahiti Village Timeshare Trip Review	I saw the ad on TV for Tahiti Village for a free 3 night stay in Las Vegas, and thought, &quot;no way, if it's too good to be true it probably is.&quot; I called anyways to see what it was all about. The operator told me that I could stay at Tahiti Village and they would give me a $100 dollar gas card to come out, the only catch was that I needed to go to thier two hour time share presentation, and put down a $98 dollar deposit. I was still sceptical but I decided to give it a try. Before I went I looked online for some reviews on how other people's experiences where with Tahiti village timeshare presentation was. I couldn't find much, (which is why I am writting this). When my boyfriend and I got to Vegas I reset our odemeter to zero so we could see if it really was only 3/4 of a mile from the Mandelay Bay Casino (which is what they told me on the phone), and it wasn't. Tahiti Village is actually about 3 1/2 miles from the MB. When we checked in we had a little trouble showing that we lived together (even though our id's show the same address, my city was miscorrectly spelled on my id, so they made us print out something from the internet showing that we actually did live together (an amazon.com reciept.). After we got that cleared up we went to our room. The room was amazing, very spacious, clean, and definatly nice.Our presentation was scheduled for the next morning at 10 am. We had had so much fun the previous night that we only got two hours of sleep. Anyways, we were introduced to our guide, and we sat down and talked for a while. He was trying to explain to us how he had bought one of their timeshares and actually sells the room for one week a year, and makes money. I didn't really believe that you could make that much money on one of their rooms being that you can stay in a room in the middle of the strip for the same amount of money. They also had a deal where if you bought one of thier timeshares you could get discounted trips to all over the world (six times a year for 7 days) for between $299-$700 (that actually did sound like a good deal.) We explained to our guide that we wanted to purchase a house first, and that it was not a good investment for us to buy one of their timeshares because we needed to save our money to put more down on a house that we could stay in 52 weeks out of the year. At the end of the presentation the closer came over and told us that the price of the larger suite (the one that we stayed in for free) for $48,000 dollars, or we could purchase the smaller room for $13,000 dollars. He tried to make thier 17.9% interest rate sound small, but we again told them no and explained how expensive a mortgage is in California, and they let us go. We went to the window to recieve our refund, and gas cards. We had no problem at all. The presentation really did only go 2 hours, but we were lucky because other (staying at other hotels had to wait for everyone to get out to ride the shuttle back) .When we checked out they asked why we were checking out at 10 instead of 11? I showed them the paper they sent me in the mail stating that check out was at 11am. They said okay and charged me nothing at all.All in all I would say that this is a very good deal. I read some reviews that people were upset that they had to sit through a two hour presentation, but they didn't appreciate the fact that if they had booked a trip to Las Vegas and paid, they would have ended up spending upwards of 1,000 dollars to stay in a room the size of thier room, and all the other &quot;gifts&quot; they give you to go out there. I would definatly take advantage of this again if I could. I only ended up spending $180 dollars total on this trip, including food, gas, gambling, going to the top of the stratusphere, ect.Hope this is helpful. Do go for the free nights, and free gifts....But do not buy it is an extreme rip off.	
