Aug 3 2008 	Perfectly Satisfied	We traded into Tahiti Village since it was taking over ten months to get confirmed into any Marriott Beach resort on the east coast. I was very leery after reading many negative reviews, but I was so very pleasantly surprised once arriving. I was with two best friends (age 40ish), my husband, my sixteen yr old daughter and her best friend. Our goal was not to do too much gambling/shows since we had the teenagers, but to see Hoover Dam, the Grand Canyon and show the girls the themed hotels, ride the roller coasters and make it to the Stratosphere rides...mostly, our goal was to relax and enjoy the pool.First with the front desk: I had requested ahead of time a poolside room on an upper floor. I was told that the sixth floor is for smoking guests, so I requested a fifth floor room. Upon arrival, I was offered Room 2101/2101A (sleeps 8), poolside, since it was available--it was 12:30 pm. We accepted, unloaded our luggage into a very spacious, clean, stone's throw away from the pool and gym room. We ate lunch at Tahiti Joe's. Our lunch was very good...service was slow. No complaints about the food though. We also picked up dinner one night to eat in our room, and again the food was very good. The front desk woman was very nice and very helpful to my husband. The fact that we were given a room immediately upon arrival was a huge bonus. We were than wisked away to the other side of the room...I was ready for this...to be offered $100 Am Ex card if we listened to the presentation. We declined since we had a timeshare presentation lined up with Marriot and we were getting $100 Visa card through them...Juana was understanding/courteous and just gave us her number in case we changed our minds. I was ready for pushiness, but it never showed. Yes, the lobby stays VERY busy with salespeople and their &quot;victims&quot;, and we saw them walking the grounds everyday and all day, but it just simply humored me. I was never bothered by any of them.I was very pleased with the cleaniness of our rooms. When supplies got low (like dishwashing detergent), we called housekeeping or simply asked the maid in the hallway. I would buy trashbags if I every stayed here again (and I would), because the one's available were of poor quality and kept breaking on me. I am used to staying in timeshares where the rooms aren't cleaned daily, so this wasn't a problem for me. If I needed new towels, I asked for them. I didn't like the laundry machines...I didn't want to dry my clothes for 140 minutes and this is what it took just to dry one pool towel. So I avoided using the machines. Odd that both machines are one. It was 105 degrees during our stay (no humidity though! so I loved it but that sun is intense!), so I didn't use the steam shower. I did love the shower though. With the door going the full length of the shower, I never got cold drying off and the bathroom never steamed up. I do agree that the toilet should be behind a door though. We dealt with that fine though. I do agree that the plasma tv should be in the main room for all to use, but I didn't mind having it to myself. The kitchen is lacking in supplies compared to Marriott rooms...we could have used baking sheets for our fries or chicken tenders or pizza rolls (could only use the 9x13 dish for one thing at a time). If I had seen the grilling area sooner, I would have used that more often. Fantastic space! Five gas grills, refrig, sinks and tables, etc. My bed was very comfortable and the girls on the sofa bed has no problems sleeping.I was concerned that the pool water would be hot since it is so shallow. It is at its deepest at 4 ft 6 inches. It was very relaxing with plenty of noodles, the beach is great for keeping the small children occupied (and keeping them out of the majority of the pool), we played volleyball often and there was basketball. The pool drinks were overpriced, but this is always the case. We did the unthinkable by staking out chairs first thing in the morning...there could be more shaded areas...but it didn't seem like anyone had problems getting chairs throughout the day. We were poolside by ten every morning. The day that activities were supposed to go on...there were none...odd. Not sure what happened there. Lifeguards were pleasant, and they seemed to be staying busy. Planes fly overhead often, but I didn't have a problem with the noise. I actually enjoyed looking up at them (they do fly low), and my family didn't have issues with them at all.Transportation...taxi to Food For Less (don't recommend this store at all) was $16 round trip. No problems ever getting taxi (we went to the strip three different days/times)...five min wait. Shuttle was a problem one night for pick up...it took 30 mins at Treasure Island but it is stated that if strip is congested, the shuttle is not timely. But the Deuce was the same...two buses passed us over due to crowds...again, 30 mins to catch one night even though they say it is 7 min wait. It just depends on season and time of day...etc. I was annoyed by both the Deuce and Shuttle those two times, but I was happy that one was free and the other was a nominal charge. Deuce picks up at the Outlet Center...very easy. Oh, within walking distance there is a McDonalds, IHOP (for those who don't want Denny's daily), Chili's, Tropical Smoothie, Outback Steakhouse...about ten min or less walk. Food Court is in the Outlet Center. Whole Foods is at Town Square. We walked through the Outlet Center, and we bought nothing...didn't need anything :)The gym has a Bowflex and four machines...small, but each time I went whether at 7:30 am or 5:00 pm, I was able to use a machine. I caught up on old tv shows. During the pm workouts though, the music was too loud. There is a sauna and shower there. The bathroom in the hall was clean, and there is a shower and bathrooms behind the waterfall at the pool.One late night back from the strip, the front desk was called by me to tell them we were hearing loud music somewhere. Fifteen mins later it was still loud and playing. My husband went to the front desk...it was the younger employees playing the music but they forgot to turn off the pool speaker (!)...we got that straightened out really quickly! I would stay at TV again and hope to get the same room on nearby. Maybe then the lazy river would be completed as well. It didn't look like it would be ready by Aug 15th...there will be a water park across the street (due 2012 though), and this will bring more to do. Don't go to TV if you want easy access to gambling and shows. Go to TV if you want apartment style living for relaxing days at the pool and an occasional jaunt to the strip.	
Jul 30 2008 	Disappointed!	Just got back on Monday. We travel to Vegas frequently and I guess are used to more. The grounds are pleasant enough but besides swimming, there is nothing to do. Most people come to Vegas to gamble, eat and party a little. This place has no casino (I new this going in), no active bar scene, and no real restaurants. Tahiti Joes is OK, but there is only a Dennys for breakfast. I don't know about you, but I don't go to Vegas to eat at Dennys. All this wouldn't be so bad if they had a decent transportation system. People fly into Vegas, and most don't rent cars. This place is miles from the strip and just about everything else. Their shuttles leave on the half our but only stop at 3 places. There is almost no taxi service to speak of. If you miss the shuttle or want to go anywhere other than the strip, you have two choices, wait a half hour (if your going to the strip), or call a taxi which taskes at least 20-30 minutes to get there. We almost got into a fight when our cab got there and 2 other parties ran out claiming it, saying, &quot;we called 30 minutes ago&quot; If your used to resort style transportation, cabs in a line waiting, forget it. I don't come to Vegas to get in line to wait that kind of time. This place feels more like an apartment complex, with proximity to the strip but you need a car to get around. I agree with the other review in that the staff is not knoledgeable or overly friendly. At least not like you'd find at a real resort. Again, more like an apartment complex staff.If you want the feel of staying at your friends apartment when in Vegas, this place fits. If your looking for that &quot;resort/vacation&quot; feel, then look elsewhere. Hope this helps!	
