May 7 2008	Buyer Beware	I will start with it looks nice and the rooms are big, while starting to build more buildings and a much bigger pool. It's also way south of the strip.  But...we went for the 3 night stay on them and took the tour. The people who work there or &quot;salesman&quot; as they might try to call themselves, were walking cliches. Our sales lady, while very nice and polite, had these huge fake orange nails, took a smoke break while I was in the bathroom for 1 minute, then stunk the rest of our conversation. We didn't say yes, so the other walking cliche 'finance manager' comes over and does his numbers on a pad of paper. Nothing there is in print; its pointing at magazines for half a second or some book. He was munching on his gum while talking in his black suit black t-shirt outfit talking about his hummer with his fake diamond encrusted rolex standing out. Cheesy cheesy cheesy! It's amazing how fast they want you to commit to dropping $25-48K after a small tour and a conversation. It's a numbers game for the people walking through the door- they don't care. I was told over 700 people per day! Just beware what you're getting into, do your research and be prepared.	
Apr 15 2008	the math doesnt add up	My New Bride and I went to Las Vegas to get married. we called the Tahiti village 800 number and made arrangements for our stay. In 2007 we had went to their other facility off decator next to a Dennys...just up the street from the Orleans. At first we thought it was a hotel and was delighted in the setup and was interested in staying there this year (08). When we spoke to the counter help she told us about the concept and gave us a short tour.We called this year and went on the tour as she had suggested.Our tour guide this time was polite and professional; however when we were given the price after several inquires it was a bit beyond our current income. My current monthly payment is 1010.00 for 2000 SF. And their payment was roughly 750 per month. The guide kept pushing that we wouldnt have to spend more than 140-170 when we travelled compaired to the 400-600 we'd spend at a regular hotel; yet thats really deceptive because if this were the case we would have forked out almost a grand on a mortgage for a tahiti village certificate that essentally said we owned a time share only days before our trip....oh im sorry a &quot;vacation ownership&quot; or whatever title they are calling it this year. What boggles my mind is how i can own it if i dont really own anything but time at one of their resorts. We dont have an actual piece of property to call our own. For instance...should i get some time in the dog house i couldnt just go to my &quot;vacation ownership&quot; and have a place to stay. Id have to call and make arrangements and hope that i get a room with a view. So really what theyre selling is vacation time. And at the high interest rates we were quoted i can only imagine what the rate woulda been in the end if i had bad credit.When we inquired about play areas for our kids the tour guide said, &quot;there is a play ground across the street.&quot; He was proud to point out the meager gym (honestly only because the development wasnt finished) and the beach like pool with a kids sand area with only one little blonde kid digging a hole (where were the parents by the way....and i dont mean the 5 life guards on duty). Now for anyone else with a five and 8 year old child you know that a sand box has a shorter entertainment life than a sand clock hour glass.In all honesty the concept and a good portion of the perks are great and we'd be interested in this when my retirement comes in the next few years. But given the treatment we recieved when we told the tour guide, the finance manager, and the marketing rep that this was not financially feasable; i'd be more inclined to just buy a property near the beach in santa monica to sneak off to for some quiet time.We must say that the Tahiti Joe's lounge and the food there was really good, the bartenders were swell and there is now a tiki mug from Tahiti joe's standing in my collection. I must thank Tahiti village for the hour of free gambling and the $100 in shell cards for the nice ride home with my lovely bride!By the way where is my $98 refund?	
Apr 14 2008 	Great place to stay especially for families	This review is for the purposes of staying at TV as a hotel, not for a time share purchase. We stayed at TV for 3 nights. We got the 1500 sqft 2 bedroom suite for $200 a night through the Entertainment Book travel site. The configuration is two separate suites with a connecting door in the middle. One of the rooms was slightly bigger with a balcony. We were on the 4th floor overlooking the pool, partial view of the Las Vegas Strip, and could see planes landing at the airport. The suite had two full bedrooms, one full kitchen, one partial kitchen, one spa tub, and one steam shower. The spa tub and steam shower were in the bigger room. We could have lived in the place for a month in the way it was setup. The adults had their own bedrooms and the children slept on the pull out beds in the living rooms. Two families could easily be comfortable in this unit.The suite was very clean and nicely maintained. Everything worked fine. The bigger suite bed room had a huge flat panel in it. The rest of the TV’s were standard tube TV’s. The décor was an “island” type theme. It was quiet despite being so close to the airport and the jet landings and takeoffs were not an issue. The balcony was good sized and nice to sit on and check out the pool. The unit had a washer/dryer also.The resort was nicely maintained and showed little signs of wear. The pool area was incredible. They have a sandy beach area and wading pool type areas for the little ones. The kids had a great time at the pool. For a family with young children who want to spend a lot of time at the pool, this is the best feature about TV. The hot tub was very nice and big also. The hot tub is open 24 hrs. Sometimes the hot tub had too many kids especially at night. The pool does not have a lazy river or any water slides.TV is not within walking distance of any casinos. They do have free shuttles going to the strip all day and night so that helps. They do have a restaurant with video poker at the bar if you need to get your fix in without leaving the resort. Oddly enough they don’t have shuttles going to the closest casinos – The Silverton and South Pointe which are south on LV Blvd. If you are interested in shopping there is an outlet mall across the street. There are also some chain restaurants fairly close by. The resort has a Denny’s on site and a restaurant – Tahiti Joes. We ate at Tahiti Joes one night and the food was very good. The bar is nice with good drink specials and quite a lively “locals” scene into the morning hours.TV is a timeshare resort so there are quite a few people being taken on “tours” by the sales staff. We were not harassed to go on a tour by anyone from TV. When we got our “Welcome Packet” from the concierge they asked if we wanted free show tickets if we would take a tour. We declined and it was no problem. I believe the concierge desk has access to half price show tickets similar to locations around Las Vegas.There is construction going on at TV – they are building a new addition to the resort. It can be a little noisy, but nothing too disruptive. The new addition is massive – 6 stories. The building in question looks to be finished with the major construction. They did have a giant crane operating when we were there – installing huge palm trees.If you want the “true” Las Vegas strip experience, then this is not the place as the location is away from the Strip. If you are looking for a casual, relaxed environment away from the chaos of the Strip, then TV would be a good choice. If you are a family looking for a nice, relaxing place to stay, with a great pool, then TV would also be a great pick.Just a few thoughts if you are planning to stay at TV. An outside upper floor room (4th floor or higher) on the north side of the resort will have a direct view of the Las Vegas strip – which at night is spectacular and the planes landing and taking off at the airport will be right in front of you. There is nothing in front of this part of the resort (because of the airport) and no street noise. It may be louder because of the airport, but the view of the Strip is spectacular. If that is not available then go with a room facing the pool area as the anything else will be overlooking the parking lot or Las Vegas Blvd.There is one minor negative about the location of TV. Next door to TV is the Manor Hotel. This hotel is low budget place with extended stay type rooms. There are some sketchy people around this hotel. Lot’s of hanging around on the balconies, drinking beer, smoking, some screaming, etc. Basically the entire outside south part of the resort faces the Manor Hotel. I would avoid any room that faces toward this place.A few other minor issues in the suite were the lack of adequate drawer space for clothes and the beds could have of higher quality -- better mattresses, have matress pads, etc. No big deal but some people are picky about stuff like this.Overall, I would highly recommend TV if you have a family or just want to avoid the madness of the Strip. It is a great value and a nice place to stay.	
