Oct 17 2007 	Great Resort	My husband and I purchased a timeshare at Tahiti Village before they even broke ground, and we are please to say that we have no regrets. We just returned from 5 days at the resort and, as usual, had a wonderful time. We have never had any issues with any of the resort personnel, and we really appreciate that they have lifeguards on duty at the pool. They are still going through construction, and even though our room was on the very end of tower 2, closest room to the construction, I was only bothered by the beeping of a truck in reverse on our last morning there. The check-out time is, in my opinion, ridiculously early at 10am, but if you call to the front desk you can request a late check-out. If you plan on seeing Vegas, I recommend getting a rental car, as the shuttle isn't always the most convenient means of seeing the sights. We always rebt a car, and I have no problem tipping the valet $2 at any of the casino's we visit. The new shopping mall is supposed to open soon, and rumor has it that there is a casino going in across the street. I think the only negative thing I have to say is that the free continental breakfast at Tahiti Joe's is a waste of time, seeing as it is only muffins, coffe and juice. Hit the grocery store down the road instead and get some toaster waffles. Lastly, if the large casino's aren't really a draw for you, or you are looking for lower ($5) table minimum's, I recommend going to the Silverton or the Southpoint, both of which are just south of Tahiti Village. The Silverton is the local's favorite casino, and we found all of our dealers very eager to help us, especially when we decided to learn craps. The Southpoint has a great staff, and we have found our favorite blackjack dealer there on both of our last two trips.	
